My take is that Elden Ring gives you such a broad variety of tools but tends to do it in unconventional ways that new players don't immediately recognise as helping them and the game intentionally gives quite little guidance on how to approach the tools for play.

One of the problems with designing accessibility is that video games often need to create meaningful challenges in order to allow play. One form of accessibility comes in the variety of tools the game gives you to overcome those challenges.

I do think though, that discourse around this game illustrates a lot of the tensions we experience when designing education for a diverse group of learners, many of whom don't make the initial choice of participating in education to begin with

These games give you a LOT of agency to learn but with that comes responsibility and admittedly that's not what everyone wants out of game because they might want to play specifically to let go of the stress that comes with agency and learning.

But on the other hand, it also means potentially going through a fair bit of the game completely unsure on how combat mechanics work in this game if you're a new player. There's a balance between agency/choice and carefully guidance here!

Take for example: missing the tutorial, which people are talking about. I like that there's a real choice given to players here compared to many games that force you through it. I like that you can make the mistake of missing it and learn a lot from that mistake about exploration

At the same time, I think that learning should be accessible and that systems should make the difficulty of learning accessible to people. So the discourse around many aspects of the game fascinate me because there's this tension.

One thing I'm very torn on wrt FromSoftware games is that I think learning is not fun. This game reflects a lot of real world learning in comparison to other games and generally it seems to me that a lot of people don't like that experience.

There's something to be said about how some approaches to foreign policy seem to conflate the symbolic gestures that threaten sovereignty with real violence against a state? I'm no expert on this though

Especially where military situations are concerned, we shouldn't forget that our vulnerability has been framed as "we are a Chinese nation surrounded by brown people". That's the historical origins of that line of thought so its dubious at best imo.

On top of that, we should also be quite concrete about what the risks Singapore faces are. For the most part, we are at risk of losing how comfortable our economy make us. The kind of collapse people are always hypotheising is something we should account for, but how real is it?

By abstracting the vulnerability of nation-states (in particular, Singapore), I feel like we frequently diminish the extent to which other counties experience real political crises, as compared to our imagined and hypothetical ones.
It's totally disingenuous to pretend that countries are on the same footing and under the same kinds of political pressures or instabilities, whether they're from the outside or in.

One thing I learnt when I got to meet ASEAN writers from the region is how naive it is to assume that the geopolitical situations of different countries can be compared to each another on some kind of one to one basis

Such interpretations of ideology have similarly dismissed the support needs of other disabled people. I think anticapitalist critique needs to be precise and attentive, or it risks being incredibly harmful to people you claim your arguments are helping.

13/13

A final important note: More people have gotten diagnosed because of greater self awareness and a realisation that there is a need for support, not because we are subject to capitalist ideology. It's quite bizzare and unfair to characterise the growing awareness this way. 

12/

At the end of the day, it is also worth noting that I'm making generalisations: every country has a different medical system and the administration of this issue, as well the mechanics of neoliberal logic, may differ. There are different strategies for optimisation.

11/

Simply put, we might choose to underdiagnose ADHD and not to provide meds when it is more costly to the system as a whole to provide support for everyone. An efficient neoliberal system would only correct (rather than support) those needed normalisation.

10/

Institutions also tend to function on neoliberal logic, which I'll oversimplify as being about optimising the economy rather than just maximising profits/productivity per se. Biopolitics would dictate only correcting the outliers where ADHD is concerned.

9/

Arguably, ADHD tends to be seen as a disorder of productivity because that's the issue we create for others but that does not mean that the issue of productivity encompasses the entirety of our experiences or how we are disabled.

8/

It also does not necessarily follow that the demand for ADHD meds is artifical simply because pharma seeks to increase profits (see, for example insulin). The entire web of issues wrt psychiatry is too complex to unpack here.

7/

It's easy to conclude that "big pharma is looking to profit off ADHD meds" or that "we diagnose ADHD to maximise productivity" but in the first place I'd disagree with framing ADHD as a disorder of productivity.

6/

I also take issue with a vague gesture towards capitalism when people do not direct their analysis towards institutions as they actually exist. When people talk about the logic of capital, they're usually referring to  the drives to maximise profit and productivity. 

5/

Moreover, these claims have to be contextualised by the fact that, generally, ADHDers have been denied diagnosis and medication. Many of us, critical of capitalism and biomedical approaches, still need this support and not just in service of capitalist institutions. 

4/

In examining ADHD in the context of capitalism, we're looking at the intersection of multiple issues: diagnosis, psychiatry, disability, medical systems and neurodiversity. The claim about ADHD has implications for all these other issues and shouldn't be carelessly made. 

3/

There are numerous problems with "ADHD only exists/you only need ADHD meds under capitalism" takes and it keeps coming up so let's first of all note the complexity of the issue and how reductive this take is.

2/

ADHD and capitalism: first off, I wanna say that there are a lot more questions we need to ask and less certain answers but it's certainly unhelpful if anticapitalist theories lead to broad generalisations that dismiss the perspectives of those it's supposed to help

@420hacker2001xo Yup! There's a lot more than just getting a kid to be focused in the moment. I have to make sure learning is rigorous but there's a whole bunch of factors I consider in terms of pacing for a student.

Of course implicit to this problem is whether kids can self assess accurately and adopt the best behaviours for themselves but really our job as teachers is to help them become better at self management, not to manage them through coercion.
If the kid that is doodling completes their work faster than if they weren't doodling and successfully answers questions about what I taught, then the doodling has helped them.

The difference comes down to this: in the classroom are you asking kids to tell you what helps them be productive? Are you checking on their understanding? Or are you just forcing them to comply with desired behaviours?

Recently had a fairly inspiring discussion about teacher attitudes: it's far more productive to reflect on how we fix our teaching methods than to try to fix children. To me, we fail as teachers often and imo this is one example of sustained failure.

If you haven't seen fidgeting help kids, it's because you're either forcing kids to comply with the behaviours of looking focused or you can't assess what's the most productive tool for the kid to use.

There are also more productive ways to fidget if stim toys end up being distracting for some kids! But generally speaking stim toys for autistic kids help them regulate sensory and emotional overload. ADHD kids need to fidget in some way to focus on things.

The basic principle is that what you see is what you remember. So make sure your digital space allows you to see what you need to remember.

Caveat: Won't help you with executive dysfunction though 😂

5/5

For more complex, larger tasks, you probably need a checklist and to only out down a check when you can put it aside mentally.

For simpler things, it can be just leaving the draft window until you have sent the email, and making sure it's not hidden behind something.

4/

I hate texts for this reason because if I close the app, there's no way to see if I sent a message until I open the app again.

So depending on what works for you/what you prefer, create a simple system that is intuitive for tracking tasks

3/

With digital tasks, it's easy to forget or misplace them because there isn't always a visual indicator for what needs to be done (contrast with, say, leaving a door open).

So we have to create some kind visual indications for ourselves to remind us of what hasn't been done

Being autistic I lean heavily towards explicit communication about trust, but I also know from experience that most people want to build trust implicitly first before they're comfortable having conversations about it. Go too fast and they suspect your motives or feel distrusted.

Here's my take: we need it to be safe enough for queer kids to come out and to have conversations about consent and sexuality with adults so that their first point of contact with these topics is not a groomer who is intentionally seeking to manipulate them
I'm just saying, let's not plunge headfirst into a topic without looking where we're going

With a topic like groomers in the LGBT community, I can see why everyone is up in arms and sometimes if you want to write a tweet about something like that you're going to need a whole PR dept to vet your tweet.

Sometimes problems like this seem to have a very operational/logistical analysis to improve inclusion/accessibility and so I think it's worth asking who is politicising the issue

I'm not sure how great this analogy is but it would be extremely weird to argue that a ramp takes away space from people using the stairs (although I'm sure there are people who make this argument albeit not through a racial lens)

In this sense accessibility is really comparable to having a ramp vs steps where having fewer options near to you means you cannot even get food. Then it is also a matter of privilege to assume that as Chinese people we should deserve variety while others don't.

Lack of options is a serious structural issue, not just about preference/variety. When there are fewer options, some people have to travel further and some places can't be reached at all, even before you take disabilities into account, due to lesson schedules

Like: isn't it quite obviously a structural/systemic issue where lack of options + physical barriers create lack of accessibility.

I think in this discussion of accessibility, we're really underestimating the extent to which enough distance creates a physical barrier

The worst thing about the halal food discourse is that we miss out on having an in-depth conversation about how systemic racism and lack of accessibility coincide because some people really colour the whole conversation with their racist perspectives

Btw also worth pointing out that such thinking tools are exactly that: tools. Student need to be taught how and when to use them; teachers also need to assess when students outgrow certain tools. They are not formulas for thinking or writing.

Consequences of a position or practice can be quantified. The scope of way you're talking about can be quantified. But what your position is on an issue should evaluate how those quantifications stack up on either side, not simply state your position as a quantity.

It is useful as a teaching tool to move beyond black and white thinking but you need to move beyond this also. Rather than vaguely quantifying your position, you should just get to the point of saying how different perspective relate or weigh up against each other.

So there's an extent to which masking for me isnt hiding or masking. It's more like categorising because when I'm trying to relate to people and not deal with information, it's a distinct set of skills and cognitive processes from my intuitive thought processes.

I may said this before, but I personally played up my ADHD in social situations in order to compensate my autistic traits because I realised people like the absent-minded goofball a lot more than the person who analyses everything to death

I think the frustrating thing about being a masked autistic is that people assume it means you can stop being autistic altogether but my entire mode of functioning is just different no matter how "successful" I am at socialising

We have information. We want to share information about our hyperfixations and ourselves. When we share this information, it doesn't have the same intentions as other people because people have "social goals" so to speak. I am rarely/never thinking about that.

But yeah I am unlearning it. I know things sometimes I don't care if I state that I know things. People will think that you're arrogant or whatever but I think I care less and less about that. People who know me will know me.
I might be too effective at all three things lol because people sometimes think I have no feelings, I feel no discomfort and know nothing 😂

- the second thing I learnt was to hide the things you know
- the third thing I learnt to hide was my physical pain and discomfort

Besides sleep, the biggest imoact for me was having time management. Having the ability to manage your time isn't about being more productive per se. I used to block out an entire Saturday for a one hour task for a lot of ADHD reasons

Personally I am not "more productive" on meds because I'm stubborn about deadlines and a perfectionist. My tasks used to bloat out indefinitely when I didn't have meds, so the main thing that suffered was my quality of life.

I want to point out that I don't take ADHD meds to improve productivity; I take them so I can sleep like a (relatively) normal human being, having better energy management during the day and manage my time so that I can actually relax
